ng public transportation, recycling, conserving energy, and avoiding single-use plastics. Governments should enforce stricter laws, promote renewable energy sources, and invest in sustainable development. Education also plays a key role in raising awareness and encouraging environmentally friendly behavior.\\n\\nIn conclusion, environmental pollution is a global issue that requires immediate attention. By working together and adopting sustainable practices, we can protect the environment and ensure a healthier future for generations to come.\\n\"',NULL,12,137,NULL,NULL,NULL,_binary '',NULL),(69,'\"https://res.cloudinary.com/decqv3ed0/video/upload/v1774811029/bvapbnubv8kec4cp0jkq.webm\"',_binary '\0',13,136,'Học sinh chưa trả lời đúng câu hỏi, cần cải thiện vốn từ và kỹ năng phát âm. Hãy cố gắng mô tả gia đình của mình một cách rõ ràng và lưu loát hơn.','{\"task_achievement\":0,\"lexical_resource\":0,\"pronunciation\":0,\"fluency\":0}',0,_binary '\0',NULL),(70,'\"**Environmental Pollution**\\n\\nEnvironmental pollution is one of the most serious problems facing the world today. It occurs when harmful substances are introduced into the natural environment, causing damage to ecosystems, human health, and wildlife. Pollution can take many forms, including air, water, and soil pollution, each with its own causes and consequences.\\n\\nAir pollution is mainly caused by the release of harmful gases and particles from vehicles, factories, and burning fossil fuels. This type of pollution leads to respiratory diseases, global warming, and climate change. Water pollution, on the other hand, happens when waste products, chemicals, and plastics are dumped into rivers, lakes, and oceans. It not only affects marine life but also contaminates drinking water sources, posing serious health risks to humans. Soil pollution is often the result of excessive use of pesticides, industrial waste, and improper disposal of garbage, which reduces soil fertility and harms agricultural productivity.\\n\\nThe causes of environmental pollution are largely linked to human activities. Rapid industrialization, urbanization, and population growth have increased the demand for energy and resources, leading to higher levels of waste and emissions. Additionally, lack of awareness and weak environmental regulations contribute to the worsening situation.\\n\\nTo address environmental pollution, both individuals and governments must take action. People can reduce pollution by using public transportation, recycling, conserving energy, and avoiding single-use plastics. Governments should enforce stricter laws, promote renewable energy sources, and invest in sustainable development. Education also plays a key role in raising awareness and encouraging environmentally friendly behavior.\\n\\nIn conclusion, environmental pollution is a global issue that requires immediate attention. By working together and adopting sustainable practices, we can protect the environment and ensure a healthier future for generations to come.\\n\"',_binary '',14,137,'Bài viết đã hoàn thành tốt yêu cầu đề bài, thể hiện sự phong phú về vốn từ vựng và cấu trúc câu. Tuy nhiên, vẫn cần cải thiện về độ chính xác ngữ pháp và liên kết giữa các đoạn văn.','{\"task_achievement\":9,\"lexical_resource\":9,\"grammar\":8,\"coherence_cohesion\":10}',36,_binary '\0',NULL),(71,'\"**Environment Pollution**\\n\\nEnvironmental pollution is one of the most serious challenges facing the world today. It occurs when harmful substances—such as chemicals, waste, or noise—are introduced into the natural environment, causing damage to ecosystems and human health. Pollution affects the air we breathe, the water we drink, and the land we depend on for food and shelter.\\n\\nThere are several main types of environmental pollution. Air pollution is caused by emissions from vehicles, factories, and the burning of fossil fuels. These pollutants release harmful gases like carbon dioxide and sulfur dioxide, contributing to global warming and respiratory diseases. Water pollution occurs when waste, chemicals, and plastics are dumped into rivers, lakes, and oceans, harming aquatic life and contaminating drinking water sources. Land pollution, on the other hand, is the result of improper waste disposal, deforestation, and excessive use of pesticides, which degrade soil quality and reduce biodiversity.\\n\\nThe causes of environmental pollution are largely linked to human activities. Rapid industrialization, urbanization, and population growth have increased the demand for energy and resources, leading to higher levels of pollution. In addition, a lack of awareness and weak environmental regulations in some regions worsen the problem.\\n\\nThe consequences of pollution are severe. It not only harms wildlife and natural habitats but also affects human health, causing diseases such as asthma, cancer, and heart conditions. Moreover, pollution contributes to climate change, which leads to rising sea levels, extreme weather events, and loss of biodiversity.\\n\\nTo address environmental pollution, both individuals and governments must take action. People can reduce waste, recycle materials, conserve energy, and use eco-friendly products. Governments should enforce strict environmental laws, invest in renewable energy, and promote sustainable development. Education and awareness also play a key role in encouraging responsible behavior.\\n\\nIn conclusion, environmental pollution is a global issue that requires immediate and collective efforts. By making conscious choices and implementing effective policies, we can protect our planet and ensure a healthier future for generations to come.\\n\"',_binary '\0',15,137,'AI grading unavailable. Please contact support.',NULL,NULL,_binary '\0',NULL),(72,'\"https://res.cloudinary.com/decqv3ed0/video/upload/v1774884819/g7m0t7onskn4rvs4nv0k.webm\"',_binary '\0',16,136,'AI grading unavailable. Please contact support.',NULL,NULL,_binary '\0',NULL),(73,'\"**Environment Pollution**\\n\\nEnvironmental pollution is one of the most serious challenges facing the world today. It occurs when harmful substances—such as chemicals, waste, or noise—are introduced into the natural environment, causing damage to ecosystems and human health. Pollution affects the air we breathe, the water we drink, and the land we depend on for food and shelter.\\n\\nThere are several main types of environmental pollution. Air pollution is caused by emissions from vehicles, factories, and the burning of fossil fuels. These pollutants release harmful gases like carbon dioxide and sulfur dioxide, contributing to global warming and respiratory diseases. Water pollution occurs when waste, chemicals, and plastics are dumped into rivers, lakes, and oceans, harming aquatic life and contaminating drinking water sources. Land pollution, on the other hand, is the result of improper waste disposal, deforestation, and excessive use of pesticides, which degrade soil quality and reduce biodiversity.\\n\\nThe causes of environmental pollution are largely linked to human activities. Rapid industrialization, urbanization, and population growth have increased the demand for energy and resources, leading to higher levels of pollution. In addition, a lack of awareness and weak environmental regulations in some regions worsen the problem.\\n\\nThe consequences of pollution are severe. It not only harms wildlife and natural habitats but also affects human health, causing diseases such as asthma, cancer, and heart conditions. Moreover, pollution contributes to climate change, which leads to rising sea levels, extreme weather events, and loss of biodiversity.\\n\\nTo address environmental pollution, both individuals and governments must take action. People can reduce waste, recycle materials, conserve energy, and use eco-friendly products. Governments should enforce strict environmental laws, invest in renewable energy, and promote sustainable development. Education and awareness also play a key role in encouraging responsible behavior.\\n\\nIn conclusion, environmental pollution is a global issue that requires immediate and collective efforts. By making conscious choices and implementing effective policies, we can protect our planet and ensure a healthier future for generations to come.\\n\"',_binary '\0',17,137,'AI grading unavailable. Please contact support.',NULL,NULL,_binary '\0',NULL),(74,'\"https://res.cloudinary.com/decqv3ed0/video/upload/v1774885692/b0fjm3fllhm4fjnaewth.webm\"',_binary '\0',18,136,'AI grading unavailable. Please contact support.',NULL,NULL,_binary '\0',NULL),(75,'\"**Environment Pollution**\\n\\nEnvironmental pollution is one of the most serious challenges facing the world today. It occurs when harmful substances—such as chemicals, waste, or noise—are introduced into the natural environment, causing damage to ecosystems and human health. Pollution affects the air we breathe, the water we drink, and the land we depend on for food and shelter.\\n\\nThere are several main types of environmental pollution. Air pollution is caused by emissions from vehicles, factories, and the burning of fossil fuels. These pollutants release harmful gases like carbon dioxide and sulfur dioxide, contributing to global warming and respiratory diseases. Water pollution occurs when waste, chemicals, and plastics are dumped into rivers, lakes, and oceans, harming aquatic life and contaminating drinking water sources. Land pollution, on the other hand, is the result of improper waste disposal, deforestation, and excessive use of pesticides, which degrade soil quality and reduce biodiversity.\\n\\nThe causes of environmental pollution are largely linked to human activities. Rapid industrialization, urbanization, and population growth have increased the demand for energy and resources, leading to higher levels of pollution. In addition, a lack of awareness and weak environmental regulations in some regions worsen the problem.\\n\\nThe consequences of pollution are severe. It not only harms wildlife and natural habitats but also affects human health, causing diseases such as asthma, cancer, and heart conditions. Moreover, pollution contributes to climate change, which leads to rising sea levels, extreme weather events, and loss of biodiversity.\\n\\nTo address environmental pollution, both individuals and governments must take action. People can reduce waste, recycle materials, conserve energy, and use eco-friendly products. Governments should enforce strict environmental laws, invest in renewable energy, and promote sustainable development. Education and awareness also play a key role in encouraging responsible behavior.\\n\\nIn conclusion, environmental pollution is a global issue that requires immediate and collective efforts. By making conscious choices and implementing effective policies, we can protect our planet and ensure a healthier future for generations to come.\\n\"',_binary '',19,137,'Bài viết đã hoàn thành tốt yêu cầu đề bài, thể hiện vốn từ vựng phong phú và độ chính xác ngữ pháp cao. Tuy nhiên, cần cải thiện hơn nữa về mặt liên kết câu và đoạn văn để tăng tính mạch lạc.','{\"task_achievement\":1,\"lexical_resource\":1,\"grammar\":1,\"coherence_cohesion\":1}',4,_binary '\0',NULL),(76,'\"Environmental pollution is one of the most serious challenges facing the modern world. As industrialization and urbanization continue to expand, the natural environment is increasingly exposed to harmful substances and destructive human activities. Pollution not only damages ecosystems but also threatens human health and the sustainability of life on Earth.\\n\\nThere are several major types of environmental pollution, including air, water, soil, and noise pollution. Air pollution is primarily caused by emissions from vehicles, factories, and the burning of fossil fuels, leading to serious health issues such as respiratory diseases and contributing to global warming. Water pollution occurs when industrial waste, chemicals, and plastic debris are discharged into rivers, lakes, and oceans, endangering aquatic life and contaminating drinking water sources. Soil pollution results from the excessive use of pesticides, fertilizers, and improper waste disposal, which reduce land fertility and affect food production. Additionally, noise pollution from traffic and construction disrupts both human life and wildlife.\\n\\nThe causes of pollution are largely linked to human activities. Rapid industrial growth, population increase, deforestation, and the overconsumption of natural resources all play significant roles. Many industries release untreated waste into the environment, while individuals often lack awareness about proper waste management. The widespread use of single-use plastics has also worsened the problem.\\n\\nThe effects of environmental pollution are far-reaching and severe. It leads to various health problems, including asthma, heart disease, and even cancer. Furthermore, pollution contributes to climate change, which causes rising temperatures, extreme weather events, and the loss of biodiversity. Ecosystems are disrupted, and many species face extinction as their natural habitats are destroyed.\\n\\nTo address this issue, both individuals and governments must take responsibility. Individuals can reduce waste, recycle materials, and adopt eco-friendly habits such as using public transportation and minimizing plastic use. Governments should implement strict environmental regulations, promote renewable energy sources, and invest in sustainable development. Education and awareness campaigns are also essential to encourage people to protect the environment.\\n\\nIn conclusion, environmental pollution is a global problem that requires urgent and collective action. By changing our behaviors and enforcing effective policies, we can reduce pollution and preserve the planet for future generations.\"',NULL,20,137,NULL,NULL,NULL,_binary '',NULL),(77,'\"Environmental pollution is one of the most serious challenges facing the modern world. As industrialization and urbanization continue to expand, the natural environment is increasingly exposed to harmful substances and destructive human activities. Pollution not only damages ecosystems but also threatens human health and the sustainability of life on Earth.\\n\\nThere are several major types of environmental pollution, including air, water, soil, and noise pollution. Air pollution is primarily caused by emissions from vehicles, factories, and the burning of fossil fuels, leading to serious health issues such as respiratory diseases and contributing to global warming. Water pollution occurs when industrial waste, chemicals, and plastic debris are discharged into rivers, lakes, and oceans, endangering aquatic life and contaminating drinking water sources. Soil pollution results from the excessive use of pesticides, fertilizers, and improper waste disposal, which reduce land fertility and affect food production. Additionally, noise pollution from traffic and construction disrupts both human life and wildlife.\\n\\nThe causes of pollution are largely linked to human activities. Rapid industrial growth, population increase, deforestation, and the overconsumption of natural resources all play significant roles. Many industries release untreated waste into the environment, while individuals often lack awareness about proper waste management. The widespread use of single-use plastics has also worsened the problem.\\n\\nThe effects of environmental pollution are far-reaching and severe. It leads to various health problems, including asthma, heart disease, and even cancer. Furthermore, pollution contributes to climate change, which causes rising temperatures, extreme weather events, and the loss of biodiversity. Ecosystems are disrupted, and many species face extinction as their natural habitats are destroyed.\\n\\nTo address this issue, both individuals and governments must take responsibility. Individuals can reduce waste, recycle materials, and adopt eco-friendly habits such as using public transportation and minimizing plastic use. Governments should implement strict environmental regulations, promote renewable energy sources, and invest in sustainable development. Education and awareness campaigns are also essential to encourage people to protect the environment.\\n\\nIn conclusion, environmental pollution is a global problem that requires urgent and collective action. By changing our behaviors and enforcing effective policies, we can reduce pollution and preserve the planet for future generations.\"',NULL,21,137,NULL,NULL,NULL,_binary '',NULL),(78,'\"Environmental pollution is one of the most serious challenges facing the modern world. As industrialization and urbanization continue to expand, the natural environment is increasingly exposed to harmful substances and destructive human activities. Pollution not only damages ecosystems but also threatens human health and the sustainability of life on Earth.\\n\\nThere are several major types of environmental pollution, including air, water, soil, and noise pollution. Air pollution is primarily caused by emissions from vehicles, factories, and the burning of fossil fuels, leading to serious health issues such as respiratory diseases and contributing to global warming. Water pollution occurs when industrial waste, chemicals, and plastic debris are discharged into rivers, lakes, and oceans, endangering aquatic life and contaminating drinking water sources. Soil pollution results from the excessive use of pesticides, fertilizers, and improper waste disposal, which reduce land fertility and affect food production. Additionally, noise pollution from traffic and construction disrupts both human life and wildlife.\\n\\nThe causes of pollution are largely linked to human activities. Rapid industrial growth, population increase, deforestation, and the overconsumption of natural resources all play significant roles. Many industries release untreated waste into the environment, while individuals often lack awareness about proper waste management. The widespread use of single-use plastics has also worsened the problem.\\n\\nThe effects of environmental pollution are far-reaching and severe. It leads to various health problems, including asthma, heart disease, and even cancer. Furthermore, pollution contributes to climate change, which causes rising temperatures, extreme weather events, and the loss of biodiversity. Ecosystems are disrupted, and many species face extinction as their natural habitats are destroyed.\\n\\nTo address this issue, both individuals and governments must take responsibility. Individuals can reduce waste, recycle materials, and adopt eco-friendly habits such as using public transportation and minimizing plastic use. Governments should implement strict environmental regulations, promote renewable energy sources, and invest in sustainable development. Education and awareness campaigns are also essential to encourage people to protect the environment.\\n\\nIn conclusion, environmental pollution is a global problem that requires urgent and collective action. By changing our behaviors and enforcing effective policies, we can reduce pollution and preserve the planet for future generations.\"',NULL,22,137,NULL,NULL,NULL,_binary '',NULL),(79,'\"Environmental pollution is one of the most serious challenges facing the modern world. As industrialization and urbanization continue to expand, the natural environment is increasingly exposed to harmful substances and destructive human activities. Pollution not only damages ecosystems but also threatens human health and the sustainability of life on Earth.\\n\\nThere are several major types of environmental pollution, including air, water, soil, and noise pollution. Air pollution is primarily caused by emissions from vehicles, factories, and the burning of fossil fuels, leading to serious health issues such as respiratory diseases and contributing to global warming. Water pollution occurs when industrial waste, chemicals, and plastic debris are discharged into rivers, lakes, and oceans, endangering aquatic life and contaminating drinking water sources. Soil pollution results from the excessive use of pesticides, fertilizers, and improper waste disposal, which reduce land fertility and affect food production. Additionally, noise pollution from traffic and construction disrupts both human life and wildlife.\\n\\nThe causes of pollution are largely linked to human activities. Rapid industrial growth, population increase, deforestation, and the overconsumption of natural resources all play significant roles. Many industries release untreated waste into the environment, while individuals often lack awareness about proper waste management. The widespread use of single-use plastics has also worsened the problem.\\n\\nThe effects of environmental pollution are far-reaching and severe. It leads to various health problems, including asthma, heart disease, and even cancer. Furthermore, pollution contributes to climate change, which causes rising temperatures, extreme weather events, and the loss of biodiversity. Ecosystems are disrupted, and many species face extinction as their natural habitats are destroyed.\\n\\nTo address this issue, both individuals and governments must take responsibility. Individuals can reduce waste, recycle materials, and adopt eco-friendly habits such as using public transportation and minimizing plastic use. Governments should implement strict environmental regulations, promote renewable energy sources, and invest in sustainable development. Education and awareness campaigns are also essential to encourage people to protect the environment.\\n\\nIn conclusion, environmental pollution is a global problem that requires urgent and collective action. By changing our behaviors and enforcing effective policies, we can reduce pollution and preserve the planet for future generations.\"',_binary '',23,137,'Bài viết của bạn đã thể hiện sự hiểu biết tốt về vấn đề ô nhiễm môi trường và các giải pháp cần thiết. Tuy nhiên, có thể cải thiện thêm về vốn từ vựng và cấu trúc câu để bài viết trở nên phong phú và mạch lạc hơn.','{\"task_achievement\":9,\"lexical_resource\":8,\"grammar\":9,\"coherence_cohesion\":10}',36,_binary '\0',NULL),(80,'\"Environmental pollution is one of the most serious challenges facing the modern world. As industrialization and urbanization continue to expand, the natural environment is increasingly exposed to harmful substances and destructive human activities. Pollution not only damages ecosystems but also threatens human health and the sustainability of life on Earth.\\n\\nThere are several major types of environmental pollution, including air, water, soil, and noise pollution. Air pollution is primarily caused by emissions from vehicles, factories, and the burning of fossil fuels, leading to serious health issues such as respiratory diseases and contributing to global warming. Water pollution occurs when industrial waste, chemicals, and plastic debris are discharged into rivers, lakes, and oceans, endangering aquatic life and contaminating drinking water sources. Soil pollution results from the excessive use of pesticides, fertilizers, and improper waste disposal, which reduce land fertility and affect food production. Additionally, noise pollution from traffic and construction disrupts both human life and wildlife.\\n\\nThe causes of pollution are largely linked to human activities. Rapid industrial growth, population increase, deforestation, and the overconsumption of natural resources all play significant roles. Many industries release untreated waste into the environment, while individuals often lack awareness about proper waste management. The widespread use of single-use plastics has also worsened the problem.\\n\\nThe effects of environmental pollution are far-reaching and severe. It leads to various heal