an effective way to present new vocabulary, as it allows learners to focus on the action rather than the doer of the action. For instance, a sentence such as \'the new policy has been implemented\' can help learners to understand the meaning of the word \'implemented\' without having to worry about who implemented it. Overall, the development of vocabulary is a complex process that requires a range of linguistic tools and strategies, including the use of relative clauses, the present perfect tense, and the passive voice.',NULL,'READING','DRAFT','Vocabulary Development',11,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-04-18 04:58:17.871326'),(33,NULL,'6.0','2026-04-18 04:58:17.874331',NULL,'The development of vocabulary has been a subject of interest for linguists and language learners alike. It has been observed that the process of learning new words is not just a matter of memorization, but rather an intricate process that involves understanding the context in which the words are used. Many language learners have reported that they have been able to learn new words more effectively when they are presented in a sentence or a short passage, rather than as isolated words. This is because the context provides clues about the meaning of the word, which can help learners to understand its connotation and usage. Furthermore, research has shown that the use of relative clauses can facilitate the learning of new vocabulary, as it allows learners to see how words are used in different grammatical structures. The present perfect tense has also been found to be particularly useful in this regard, as it enables learners to describe actions that started in the past and continue up to the present. In addition, the passive voice has been shown to be an effective way to present new vocabulary, as it allows learners to focus on the action rather than the doer of the action. For instance, a sentence such as \'the new policy has been implemented\' can help learners to understand the meaning of the word \'impl